Arrays:
- non - primitive data type
 -> data types determine what kind of data types can be stored into a variable
- fundamental data structure that allows to store multiple elements of the same data type
    -> it allows efficient access and manipulation of the data
    -> support primitive and non-primitive data types (objects)
    -> has unique index num for each element

Why use Arrays/ Why store multiple values into one variable
- one variable for multiple data
- Array helps group related data items together (list of names, list od scores etc.)
    -> allows fast and direct access to indiv elements based on their index
    -> allows to process each element easily with the help of loos
    -> offers efficient algorithm implementations for searching , sorting, and counting

Memory allocation of Arrays
- when array is created , a memory is allocated for its elements in a contiguous block in Heap.
- size of the block is determined by num of elements in the array and the size of each element
- memory allocation of primitive and non-primitive data types is different

Memory Allocation of Primitive data type Arrays
    -> Array stores actual values directly in the memory locations reserved for each array element
    -> each element occupies a fixed amount of memory determined by the size of data type
    -> e.g. int array of size 5 will allocate 20 bytes of memory

Memory Allocation of Non-Primitive data type Arrays
    -> memory is required for the object references and for the objects themselves:
        -> each element hold a reference to the actual object, and these references are stored in contiguous blocks
        -> actual objects are allocated in separated memory location

  ==>> primitive memory allocation: fixed amount of memory (objects' size depends ond JVM & OS version)
