Reference Types vs Primitive Types
- reference types and primitive types are two different kinds of data types in progr. lang.
    -> they represent different ways of storing and accessing data in memory

Primitive Data Types:
- store actual value of data
- local primitives are stored on the stack
- have fixed sizes
- when assigned to another variable or passed as an argument, a copy of its value is created
- value directly accessible and modifiable

Reference Data Types:
- store the memory address (reference) of data
- stored on the Heap, references stored on the stack
- have flexible sizes
- when reference type assigned to another variable / passed as argument,
  only reference(memory address) is copied, not actual data
- value accessed indirectly through the reference, and modifications made to actual data on heap

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Pass-by-Value vs Pass-by-Reference

- when a parameter is passed by reference,
  caller(function calling other functions) & callee(function called by another function)
  use same variable for parameter. If callee modifies parameter variable,
  effect is visible to caller's variable
- when a parameter is passed by value, the caller & callee have two independent variables with the same value
  If the callee modifies the parameter variable, the effect is not visible to the caller

  => Java is pass-by-value
